# html — skill-local configuration (TEMPLATE).
#
# ENCAPSULATION: copy to `.env` IN THIS DIRECTORY and the html CLI **auto-loads it** at startup
# (the shim reads `<skill>/.env`). The config thus travels WITH the skill — any caller that RUNS THE
# CLI (`html` directly or via the `~/.claude/skills/html` symlink — a project, wiki-import,
# a cron job) picks it up with ZERO awareness, WITHOUT polluting the machine-global environment. You
# do NOT need to `export` anything or edit ~/.zshrc. (An in-process `import html2md; main()` caller
# bypasses the shim and is NOT auto-configured — run the CLI, or call `_load_skill_env()` yourself.)
#   • Process env WINS: a variable already set in the environment is never overridden (callers can
#     still override per-run).
#   • `.env` holds secrets → keep it OUT of git (gitignored) and **chmod 600** (a group/world-
#     accessible or symlinked `.env` is IGNORED with a warning).
#   • Disable auto-load with HTML_NO_DOTENV=1 (the test suite sets this for determinism).
# EVERYTHING here is OPTIONAL: with none set, html behaves exactly as the default
# (lite→chrome→jina ladder), no crash.
#
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#  HOW THESE COMBINE (read this first)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#  There are 3 INDEPENDENT groups — set any mix of them; they do not interfere:
#     A. Remote reader   (used by --engine jina|remote, and as the auto-ladder's last resort)
#     B. Web search      (used by --search "QUERY")
#     C. Authenticated Chrome (used by --engine chrome — login-gated pages)
#  WITHIN group C the auth sources are MUTUALLY EXCLUSIVE — pick exactly ONE.
#  Cross-rule (CLI, not env): --chrome-* auth is never combined with --search.
#
#  ┌─ QUICK START — what to set for common cases ──────────────────────────────────────────┐
#  │ • Just download login-gated pages on ONE site you're logged into (e.g. X):            │
#  │       HTML_CHROME_COOKIES_FILE=~/.html/x-cookies.txt        (group C, one source)│
#  │ • Logged into SEVERAL sites, route per domain (smaller blast radius):                  │
#  │       HTML_CHROME_AUTH_MAP=~/.html/auth-map.json            (group C, the map)   │
#  │ • Also want anti-bot/Cloudflare PUBLIC pages to resolve better: add (independent):     │
#  │       JINA_API_KEY=jina_xxx                                       (group A)            │
#  │ • Nothing set → default ladder still works (just no auth, no key).                     │
#  └───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#  All file paths below must be chmod 600 (group/world access & symlinks are refused).

# ─── A. Remote reader tier (TASK 023) — vendor-agnostic URL→content for --engine jina|remote ───
# Built-in default is jina (https://r.jina.ai/). These COMBINE: PROVIDERS > URL (precedence);
# a token/key authenticates whichever reader you use. Default jina works with NO vars here.
# HTML_READER_PROVIDERS=https://reader-a.example/ https://reader-b.example/  # space/comma list; wins over URL
# HTML_READER_URL=https://reader.internal.example/   # single self-hosted/compatible reader
# HTML_READER_TOKEN=                 # bearer token for a generic/self-hosted reader (NOT jina)
# JINA_API_KEY=                         # raises the (otherwise keyless, rate-limited) jina quota

# ─── B. Web search (TASK 023) — vendor-agnostic provider for --search "QUERY" ───
# Built-in default is s.jina.ai. COMBINE: PROVIDERS > URL. Independent of groups A and C.
# HTML_SEARCH_PROVIDERS=https://s.jina.ai/           # space/comma list; wins over URL
# HTML_SEARCH_URL=https://search.internal.example/

# ─── C. Authenticated Chrome (TASK 024/026) — login-gated content via --engine chrome ───
# Pick EXACTLY ONE of the four below (mutually exclusive). All are BEARER CREDENTIALS →
# point at chmod-600 files; never inline a secret value here.
#
#  C1–C3: ONE fixed source for ONE login bundle. Mint a storage_state with:
#     python3 scripts/html login https://x.com --save-state ~/.html/x.json
# HTML_CHROME_STORAGE_STATE=/secrets/x.json     # primary: portable, read-only, server/concurrency-safe
# HTML_CHROME_COOKIES_FILE=/secrets/cookies.txt # cookie-only (Netscape cookies.txt)
# HTML_CHROME_USER_DATA_DIR=~/.html/profile  # persistent profile (LOCAL only; single-concurrency)
#
#  C4: per-domain MAP (TASK 026) — for MULTIPLE logged-in sites; routes by target domain.
#  Use INSTEAD OF C1–C3 (cannot be combined with them). Forces chrome ONLY for a mapped domain;
#  unmapped targets keep the normal ladder. The map AND every file it points to must be chmod 600.
#  JSON: { "x.com": {"cookies_file": "~/.html/x-cookies.txt"},
#          "medium.com": {"storage_state": "~/.html/medium-state.json"} }
# HTML_CHROME_AUTH_MAP=~/.html/auth-map.json
#
#  C-scroll: pull lazy content (X articles/threads materialize only AFTER scrolling). Env parity
#  for --chrome-scroll so an env-only caller (e.g. wiki-import) gets full posts. Needed for X.
# HTML_CHROME_SCROLL=1
# HTML_CHROME_SCROLL_PASSES=8

# ─── D. SSRF carve-out — ranges to ALLOW that are otherwise refused as non-public ───
# Independent of A/B/C. The fetch SSRF gate refuses any target resolving to a private/
# internal/reserved IP (RFC 1918, loopback, 169.254 cloud-metadata, TEST-NET, doc ranges, …).
# This var SUBTRACTS specific CIDRs from that block-set — comma/space-separated CIDR list.
# It is ALWAYS explicit — there is NO built-in code default:
#   • UNSET or "" (empty): NO carve-out — every non-public range stays blocked (fail-safe).
#   • a CIDR list: exactly those ranges are allowed (nothing implicit is added).
#   • 0.0.0.0/0: deliberately disables IPv4 SSRF protection (trusted local config only).
# The active line below is the SHIPPED default: 198.18.0.0/15 (RFC 2544 benchmarking). IANA
# marks it non-global, but local resolvers (ENS / `.limo` gateways, some VPNs) map REAL public
# hostnames into it (e.g. vitalik.eth.limo) — so it is allowed by default via THIS file. Comment
# it out (or set empty) for the strictest posture; append more ranges with commas.
# ⚠ A range you allow becomes reachable from this host. For untrusted input use --no-remote +
#   an egress-restricted sandbox (the gate is resolve-then-connect — see KNOWN_ISSUES HTML2MD-4).
HTML_SSRF_ALLOW_NETS=198.18.0.0/15            # e.g. "198.18.0.0/15, 10.0.0.0/8" to also allow an internal range
